<h2>The Background</h2>

<p>Many of these would-be competitors have tried to take on Facebook, with the
recent Google Plus shutdown being one of the more dramatic failures. Given the
long history, we need a lot of backstory to unpack what's going on here.</p>

<p>First, let's distinguish between a General Purpose Social Network (GPSN)
and a Special Purpose Social Network (SPSN) (though there's a lot of grey area
here). Many of [%
Ovid.cite('https://medium.com/utopiapress/facebook-lost-15-million-users-in-the-united-states-since-2017-705155060c4f',
'the millions leaving Facebook for Instagram' ) %], are leaving a GPSN for a
SPSN. Instagram is for sharing photos and videos.  If you have no photos or
videos to share, you may not find an Instagram account as appealing, though
you may have one to follow others.  [% Ovid.add_footnote("Quite a few of the
people leaving Facebook are doing so for Instagram, even if they don't
participate directly. I wonder how many realize that they're actually leaving
Facebook for Facebook?") %] Twitter is closer to a GPSN, but it's still rather
limited in its features (that, in itself, is a feature).  Facebook, like
Myspace, or the now-defunct Google Plus, is a GPSN. It has a wide variety of
features that appeal to many people. Want to connect but don't want to share
photos? Facebook. Want to connect and don't want to be limited to 280
characters? Facebook. Want to connect and regularly organize or participate in
local events? Again, Facebook.</p>

<p>GPSNs are more geared towards general-purpose social networking without
trying to shoehorn you into a particular mode of sharing. While many people
enjoy a variety of social networks, [%
Ovid.cite('https://www.invespcro.com/blog/social-media-engagement/', 'Facebook
dominates in in terms of daily user engagement' ) %], with half of its users
logging on more than once a day.</p>

<p>The distinction between GPSN and SPSN is important because this article is
only focusing on the former. The latter gets lots of traction in narrower
markets and has a robust, lively community of competitors. GPSNs are pretty
much "Facebook or nothing" as of this writing.</p>

<h1>The Problem</h1>

<p>Before we can really get down to the business case for a Facebook
competitor, we need to understand what&rsquo;s wrong with Facebook. Once we
do that, we can understand why so many David&rsquo;s have falled before this
Goliath. And once we <em>do</em> understand what is wrong with Facebook, the
failures become almost obvious given 20-20 hindsight.</p>

<p>First, let&rsquo;s be crystal-clear about what Facebook has done right:
they&rsquo;ve created a generic product that has <em>everyone with an internet
connection as their target market</em>. If you can connect to the net and you
want to be social, Facebook is perfect for you.  Of course, if you say
"everyone is my target market" to an investor, that&rsquo;s a quick way to get
them to leave, but given Facebook&rsquo;s 2 billion+ user accounts, we really
do have a serious "everyone" claim here (for would-be investors: I have a more
serious comment later in this article).</p>

<figure class="image">
    <img src="/static/images/smiling-for-camera.jpg" width="600" alt="An image of three women smiling for a smartphone picture being taken by the man next to them.">
    <figcaption>We are social by nature. <a href="https://www.pexels.com/photo/three-smiling-women-beside-man-holding-smartphone-1547468/" target-"_blank">Source</a></figcaption>
</figure>

<p>Second, given that so many people on the net want to be social, the second
major thing that Facebook has done right is not being absolute shit at what
they do. That sounds ridiculous, but when you look at the clown car of
wanna-be competitors, it&rsquo;s amazing how many of them actually got
traction, but fell down because they weren&rsquo;t up to the job,
technically.</p>

<p>Third, given the fact that the Facebook product, in an of itself, is rather
limited, they&rsquo;ve been smart enough to [%
Ovid.cite('https://developers.facebook.com/docs', 'offer APIs to allow others
to build value for Facebook') %], something that, given their reach, allows
them to offer much more to the public without having to build it
themselves. Just look at all of those annoying game requests you get to begin
to understand whats' happening here.</p>

<p>So what has Facebook done wrong? Just about everything else.</p>

<p>After being relentlessly pummeled by Facebook-related horror stories, I
finally said "enough" and started really digging in to understand what is
wrong with Facebook. I've found three major problem areas that need to be
solved, but they generally have the root cause of being a secretive,
unaccountable company focused primarily on profits and market domination. As a
businessman, I will humbly suggest that there is <em>nothing</em> wrong with
that. Honestly, you want to make money and kill your competitors? That's
perfectly fine. Where I draw the line is <em>ethics</em>. In this case,
Facebook has such a huge impact on the public sector that excluding itself
from accountability and acting in complete secrecy has created a monster.
Ironically, Facebook has been so horrifying, and there have been so few
interesting competitors, that people are suffering "compassion fatigue" and when
Facebook does something awful, they just ignore it or share it on
Facebook. Things that would kill any other company are shrugged off for
Facebook.</p>

<p>So I dug in, hard, trying to get to the bottom of this. I've read so many
articles about Facebook and their atrocities that I fear I'm becoming numb to
them, but that means I can give you a summary and spare you the worst.</p>

